1541605437-Primary nickel (II) bis(amino.title: Primary nickel (II) bis(aminoguanidine) perchlorate
1541605437-Primary nickel (II) bis(amino.description: Product of an attempt to prepare nickel (II) bis(aminoguanidine) perchlorate by reacting nickel acetate, ammonium perchlorate and AGu bicarbonate in water. The compound appears as needle like crystals or small prisms, larger ones are almost blood-red colored (maybe the compound is polluted with complexed 1,1,4,10,10-pentaamino-2,3,5,6,8,9-hexaazadeca-1,3,5,7,9-pentaene?), smaller crystals appear to be brick-red/dark orange. In open, already small pinch sized amounts on ignition explode loudly with a large flash, no DDT with such amounts - they usually did not puncture the paper under them, while the same or even smaller amounts wrapped in aluminium foil detonate, punching holes in beer cans or easily initiating pressed PETN. Explosions of larger amounts, even unconfined, are becoming very violent - it is NOT a "safe" or "mild" primary like e.g. nickel tris(hydrazine) nitrate (but is less inflammable than the hydrazinate nitrate) and the patent says, it outperforms RDX in detonation pressure, so be careful. It is soluble in water and it looks like that even in alcohol or acetone, with gradual, partial or complete decomposition, forming dirty-green solutions. Since the patent says nothing about sensitivity and stability in details, I finely ground a few tiny crystals in mortar - without explosion and I left a sample in the woods, to see if it will decompose.

1560967969-CHP Chopper Hexamine Perchlor.title: CHP Chopper Hexamine Perchlorate synthesis
1560967969-CHP Chopper Hexamine Perchlor.description: CHP was developed in 2015 as an ecological replacement for primary blends in some applications. Its production is without the use of poisons, carcinogenic substances and strong acids and without difficult available compounds. Also preparation in close jar is without smell. The resulting substance is also not toxic. Material has low sensitivity to friction, but responds well to glowing fiber, laser, or fire. On open area this substance burn only. In a closed cavity, the burning passes to supersonic speed. At high density 1,85 - 1,91 g/cc provide pressure of gases 25 GPa (250 000 Bar). Speed of wave at high density can be up to 7500 m/s. Therefore CHP can replace also secondary materials. Is possible his used as monomaterial in one device without next compounds. Confirmed is storage without changes of properties 1 year in closure glass jar at 15 Celsius. Developed in Liptakov Lab. 2015. CHP can also be prepared from 10g TACP + 1.5g hexamine under the same conditions as in the video

1579624202-I Made My OWN DIY MATCHES!.mp.title: I Made My OWN DIY MATCHES! How to make Match composition
1579624202-I Made My OWN DIY MATCHES!.mp.description:
39% SiO2, 4,7%S, 3,11% Gelatine, 1% K2Cr2O7, 1%Sodium Alginate, 48,8% KClO3, You can use without Sodium Alginate and gelatine with Animal glue, Dextrin or Gum Arabic.
Do not repeat the experiments shown in this video!
Hi everyone! In this video not only do I want to tell you about how matches are made but also to make my own matches. After that I will check how they will differ from shop-bought ones. Let us start off with a little bit of history. First predecessors of modern matches were invented in Ancient China. Those early matches were used only to simplify the process of starting a fire and It was just ordinary sulfur spread onto thin sticks. In Europe matches began to appear in 19-th century and in its early form they were very dangerous because they could light up upon friction against any surface which was quite dangerous as they could even light up in a box of matches having rubbed against each other. First safe matches appeared in 1855 and they were invented by a Swedish chemist, Johan Lundstrem. Since then they have practically remained unchanged. These Swedish matches are the very ones I am going to make in this video. Matches making starts with the simplest step which is preparing the wooden sticks which are also called strips. Such sticks are most frequently made from aspen but since I dont have it I am going to use ordinary birch toothpicks and also barbecue skewers for bigger matches. The first step of making matches is soaking sticks in fire retardant that is in chemical that prevents wood smouldering. The thing is when wood burns down the leftover charcoals that continues to smoulder turning into light ash that can cause lots of inconveniences when it get onto clothes or valuable items. To prevent unwanted outcomes when using matches they get soaked in 2% ammonium dihydrogen phosphate that is in phosphoric acid and ammonium salt acid. After soaking and drying sticks we can see that the charred heads dont smoulder which is a lot more convenient. I have quite ancient matches which are more than 100 years old. They were made in Revel which was the name of the modern day Tallinn during monarchy era until 1917. They still burn well but because of not being soaked in fire retardant, the burn down match heads fall off very quickly and keep burning which can cause ignition or even fire. That is the reason why soaking in fire redantant is such a necessary measure to take. Nevertheless sticks have to be soaked in combustible liquid that will simplify ignition of wood and consume most energy. Most frequently paraffin is used for those purposes. I melted down a paraffin candle and dipped chopped sticks. They looks like a deep-fryer and wooden chips which are fried in it. It is noteworthy that when such matches burn they give off a pleasant smell because wood contains sugars that give off a pleasant smell when burned.

1597144015_1KsFe6vgVpNFCNTQDQryrcQYySkAb.body: Project summary aka Dmitry's FAQ: [Q] How many kWh used per 1kg of acid? [A] Oh, i don't know realy. I have 1 KW on solar panels on my roof. So the energy it takes to make acid is for free.  [Q] Did you run the bubblers in "series" to make them dissolve in the water more efficiently? [A] Yes in series...I harvest  the first one if the color is getting brown ( Nitric acid is around 45% at this point ).This takes a few weeks. fill with new di water and place it at the end. It's a rotating system ;-)  [Q]  Is that first empty bottle intended to cool the gas before bubbling?  [A] Yes, to cool and reacting NO1 with air to get NO2. I removed it at a later stage. Seems it's not so critical.  [Q] I want to use multiple electrodes to improve efficiency. [A] Multiple electrodes is not recommended. The glass bottle gets really hot using 1 spark gap alone. If you want more acid its better to cascading multiple setups.  [Q] Would copper pipes be better? [A] Don't use copper in this setup.Glas / stainless steel / Teflon or HMPE only.Silicon tubing don't last long and gets brittle.  [Q] How strong is the output after distillation? [A] After 1 distillation the acid was around 53 %. The text in the video is hardcoded so I can't change it.  [Q] What did you use for your high voltage generator? Neon Sign Transformer or an Flyback Transformer? [A] I'ts a 40 Watt neon transformer.Around 6000 Volts. Spark consumes 6000 volts at around 20mA to 30mA. (should be 120-180 Watt, but in other comment Roger Jonker mentioned 40 Watt, then it should only consume 6-7mA at 6kV)  [Q] Name of the used bottles? Also what is white stuff on the bottom of bottles? [A] Can't give you a link for the bubblers, got them from a used lab equipment site and are sold out. The label on the flask says: JENAERGLAS Rasotherm.Made in GDR (note: GDR=German Democratic Republic does not exist since 1990:). White stuff on the bottom - came with the bottle. Its glass spongy / filtery material.  Dmitry edit: search ebay/amazon/other for "Gas Washing Bottle" to find similar ones. Also the "bubbler" white piece is called "frit". I guess it would be easier to just use aquarium air pump bubble stone made of quartz sand (basically made of glass!) Remember: anything touching nitric acid must be made out of glass or teflon.  [Q] please give us more info! [A] Sorry not this time.......moving to other projects. All information is in internet to find.  Dmitry's note: in the 1st bottle "oxidation tower" you have long and short pipes. Which one is "in" which one is "out"? Both nitric oxide and nitrogen dioxide are heavier than air so they would go down, but molar mass of oxide is only 30 g/mol while dioxide is 46 g/mol, so I would guess in order to get dioxide you'd use your long pipe as your "output" from the "oxidation tower"?  In this case I would make it all the way to the bottom to increase dioxide purity a bit :-)  Update (October 2019): I've build couple prototypes, used old TV flyback transformer + NE555 timer, here's the schematics: "Weekend Projects: Make a 100KV Singing Arc Plasma Speaker Flyback Driver!"  instructables: https://www.instructables.com/id/build-a-singing-ark-plasma-speaker-ongoing-proj/  and the video from the same guy: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EMiPV2YZHo8  Here's another guy showing how to fine-tune frequency of the NE555 - best explanation video imho: "How to Control the Duty Cycle of a 555 Timer" https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Z7kTCSZG5E  Also: NO need to make Jacobs Ladder setup - it is much less efficient in terms of NO2 production. We want fry/burn air, not tickle it!  : )    Just stably burning arc produces much quicker high yield of dark brown gas. To make a good fat stable arc (which produce no any noise btw) you should fine tune frequency of NE555 generated signal (easy enough - just replace static 10K resistor with variable resistor and play around - there will be a range of values where arc is visually "more happy" and much fatter and brighter). The best arc is achieved when your L-C contour is in resonance mode (I'm talking about primary 5 turns L and C ) - for 2 different setups I've build the best frequencies were slightly different (one was ~36KHz, other around 42KHz). Now, since white-burning stable fat arc is producing lots of heat (thing of it as a big candle burning) one should not use small container (as spherical one with 3 inputs shown in the video I'm commenting now: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5TjFQMGizYM ). Instead it is easier to use wide mouth glass jar (often times can be found free in recycle bins), say anything more than 5-6 litters is good (10-12 litters even better, it will have bigger surface to dissipate the heat produced by arc).  I'll keep updating this comment as I go (just ordered air compressors to play with - they have no motors, so can last much longer (cheap and simple compressors with motor and plastic parts supposed to work only around 2500 hours, which is only 100 days of non-stop work before they can officially die, not good).   Here's the compressor on ebay: 3-16L Mini Vacuum Air Pump Aquarium Air Pump 2sets Start For Tube Ozone after 10 months link to ebay item no longer works, but here's identical compressor with no motor inside: Ozonizer 4L Min Ozone Generator Air Pump Ozone Generator Parts Aquarium Air Pump   For bubblers I also already ordered aquarium bubbler (made of quartz sand baked together (think of it as a "glass" in terms of materials)) - this should survive for long time in acid: Aquarium Air Bubble Creator Quartz sand, 14.5 mm, 5 Pieces, Blue C6R3
See more about the setup in C&P Forum http://127.0.0.1:43110/13WfLQv2nWXYBNUEL3PkWwGUe3H7qkTF5Y/?Topic:1600447289_1KsFe6vgVpNFCNTQDQryrcQYySkAbFLXCV/Make+nitric+acid+at+home
